        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:22px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Moldova‚Äôs Close EU Vote</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Moldova narrowly voted to join the European Union, with <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/moldova-narrowly-votes-yes-to-eu-membership/a-70544401" target="_blank">50.4% supporting</a> the constitutional change to enshrine EU membership and 49.6% opposing it. The results almost appeared to be a ‚Äúno‚Äù  until late Monday morning when the Moldovans abroad came in. This election happened amid accusations of <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/moldovas-eu-referendum-beset-by-alleged-russian-meddling/a-70527782" target="_blank">Russian interference</a> through vote-buying and propaganda. Pro-Western President Maia Sandu blamed foreign forces for the tight race. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">This victory for the pro-EU side is seen as a defeat for Russia. Moldova is now focused on completing EU accession talks, aiming for membership by 2030, but this isn‚Äôt a guarantee as EU accession can take over a decade. Moldova has many issues to settle and obstacles (<a href="https://www.geopolitics.world/archives/poverty-affects-billion-hamas-leader-killed-moldova-to-eu" target="_blank">see our write-up</a>). </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
